# Copy this file to `.env` and fill in the values. `.env` is gitignored —
# never commit it, and never paste real values into chat or a pull request.
#
# NOTE: use `.env`, NOT `.env.local`. Supabase's setup page suggests
# `.env.local`, but the Prisma CLI only reads `.env` — migrations and the
# seed script would fail to find the connection string. Next.js reads `.env`
# too, so a single `.env` serves both.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# REQUIRED — Supabase Postgres connection strings.
#
# Where to find them: Supabase Dashboard -> OpsHub project ->
#   Connect -> ORMs -> Prisma
#
# Two URLs, on purpose:
#   DATABASE_URL — transaction-mode pooler, port 6543. Used for app queries.
#                  Serverless functions borrow a pooled connection instead of
#                  exhausting Postgres with direct ones.
#   DIRECT_URL   — session-mode pooler, port 5432. Used for migrations, which
#                  cannot run under pgbouncer's transaction pooling.
#
# Both contain your database password — these are the only secrets OpsHub
# needs. Treat them like passwords.

# Copy the exact strings from the dashboard — they already contain your
# project ref and region. Shape shown here for reference only:

DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.[PROJECT-REF]:[YOUR-PASSWORD]@aws-0-[REGION].pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?pgbouncer=true"
DIRECT_URL="postgresql://postgres.[PROJECT-REF]:[YOUR-PASSWORD]@aws-0-[REGION].pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTIONAL — enables AI-phrased insight text.
# Without it, OpsHub falls back to built-in template text and works fully.
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Deliberately NOT used by OpsHub:
#
#   SUPABASE_ANON_KEY / SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY
#
# OpsHub talks to Postgres only through Prisma over the URLs above; nothing in
# the app uses supabase-js. Storing those keys would mean holding extra
# secrets that nothing reads — and service_role bypasses every security rule.
# The database is locked down instead: RLS is enabled with no policies and
# the anon/authenticated roles are revoked, so the public API grants zero
# access. See prisma/migrations/*_enable_rls_deny_all/migration.sql
